The write-down of European debt is inevitable
Berkeley – – "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think, but not anymore, because it's clearly a eurozone crisis.
To deal with it, is both easier and harder than usually anticipated.
The economics of this crisis are fairly straightforward.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Irish banking has problems.
Portuguese private bond markets have problems.
Spain has problems on all three counts.
Though the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries will have to go through painful spending-cut processes.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic cuts with currency devaluation.
Devaluation would enhance export competitiveness, that is, using external demand to make up for internal demand.
But these countries are all in the eurozone and do not have their own currencies for devaluation, so they can only substitute internal devaluation for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, the resolve of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is considerable.
But one economic variable has not changed with the adjustments of other variables, and that is the debt of both the public and private sectors.
Government accumulated debts are not changing on the balance sheet, and bank debts — except for some junior creditor debts — are also largely unchanged.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy in a self-defeating position: the more wage and other cost cuts are made, the relatively heavier the burden of accumulated debts becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more expenditure cuts and tax increases are needed to meet government and its protectors (such as banks)’ debt obligations.
This, in turn, requires further internal devaluation, pushing up the debt burden even more, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a recessionary trap.
So, for internal devaluation to work, ways must be found to reduce the face value of debts.
Government debts must be restructured.
Bank debts must be converted into equity, and banks insolvent should have their debts written off.
Mortgage debts also need to be reduced.
Policy makers may not want to go down this road, and that is understandable.
Contracts are sacred.
<s>Government worries about losing credibility with financial markets.
<s>If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, writedowns could drag down other countries.
<s>These concerns cannot be dismissed, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
<s>The only solutions are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
<s>European leaders must choose one of the two.
<s>They consistently ruled out external devaluation.
<s>But internal devaluation inevitably requires debt restructuring.
<s>Denying this point makes neither sense nor logical sense.
<s>The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward.
<s>The government can issue a batch of bonds at a discount rate relative to the existing debt face value.
<s>Bondholders can choose either to hold onto their bonds at face value but with a longer maturity and lower interest rates, or to accept discounted bonds with a shorter maturity and higher interest rates.
<s>This is not cutting-edge technology; it has been done before.
<s>But for it to work, there are three prerequisites.
<s>First, the safety of the new bonds must be assured to bondholders.
<s>Someone must come forward to guarantee these bonds.
During the 1980s, when Latin American debt was restructured under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "guarantor big brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, each country must act in unison.
Otherwise, the restructuring of one country would raise expectations for others, leading to a contagion effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses due to the debt restructuring must see their balance sheets strengthened.
<s>These banks need real stress tests rather than the charade conducted earlier this year.
<s>If debt restructuring signals capital shortfalls, then the relevant banks need comprehensive equity conversions.
<s>If that is not enough, governments must inject capital into the relevant banks.
<s>This too requires coordinated action across countries.
<s>Once bank balance sheets are solidified, it may be possible to restructure mortgage, bank, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's turn to the greatest challenge.
This all requires strong leadership.
German leaders must recognize the size of their country's banking exposure to the debts of eurozone peripheral countries, and that the situation is urgent.
They must convince the backroom bosses and the electorate that using public funds to underwrite debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation—a strategy Germany has been urging on other EU countries and one that it should be willing to back with its own guarantees.
In short, European leaders, particularly those in Germany, need to put a much harsher spin on the implications—if they do not, the consequences will be dire.
Because that is the reality.
